{"type":"message","id":"aaccec35","parentId":"f494b08b","timestamp":"2026-04-17T16:25:28.453Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"OK, so the auto-score-classify hook fires on `message:preprocessed`. This is the right event - after the message is preprocessed (classified + scored), but before the agent receives it.\n\nThe hook can:\n1. Classify and score\n2. Write to ephemeral\n3. Based on score, take additional action (like spawning a subagent)\n\nThe key insight is: if I create a hook that fires on `message:preprocessed`, reads the score from ephemeral, and if score > threshold, uses a tool or gateway API to automatically spawn a subagent - that would achieve automatic routing.\n\nBut the challenge is: hooks run as separate processes. They don't have direct access to spawn subagents. The spawning happens through the gateway's RPC.\n\n\nNow I'm thinking through how to actually implement this. I could leverage the `agent:preparing` or `agent:start` events to intercept before the agent runs, then use the gateway's RPC mechanism to spawn a subagent based on the score. The `openclaw agent` CLI command could execute this, or I could look at how the existing task flow system spawns subagents automatically. I need to examine the gateway API to understand what RPC calls are available for spawning agents.","thinkingSignature":"581ba0eafec1a93bbfa632ba7a2d1b8121b43cb63cab1f13f9c36235383f38b7"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_7dv0uyz4g1yo_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cat ~/.openclaw/v8/src/router/api.js 2>/dev/null | grep -A5 \"spawn\\|subagent\\|agent.*spawn\\|sessions_spawn\" | head -30"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":103236,"output":316,"cacheRead":21638,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":125190,"cost":{"input":0.0309708,"output":0.0003792,"cacheRead":0.00129828,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.03264828}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776443118578,"responseId":"063191