{"type":"message","id":"f3229580","parentId":"522de563","timestamp":"2026-04-17T16:25:39.198Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"No direct spawning in the API router. Let me think about this differently.\n\nThe `sessions_spawn` tool is a built-in tool available to agents. The question is: can a hook trigger an agent to use `sessions_spawn`?\n\nA hook runs as a separate process. A hook could theoretically:\n1. Read the score from ephemeral\n2. If score > threshold, send a \"fake\" agent command to the gateway that tells the agent to spawn a subagent\n\nBut that's convoluted.\n\nThe cleaner approach: a hook that fires on `agent:preparing` (if such event exists), checks the score, and if high enough, uses the gateway's RPC to spawn a subagent BEFORE the main agent starts.\n \nLet me explore whether `agent:preparing` is actually a thing in the gateway, or if I need to use the ACP protocol to spawn agents from outside the session. That might be cleaner than trying to inject agent commands.\n\nActually, stepping back—the simplest solution might just be adding routing rules to the gateway config. If OpenClaw supports routing configurations that automatically route to subagents based on conditions like score thresholds, I could configure that instead of building custom logic.","thinkingSignature":"34dad8b84d52ac2eae5424c95f4a21528e65375935d04c23ab7918b762129709"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_vwoija2ltlin_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"node ~/.nvm/versions/node/v22.22.1/lib/node_modules/openclaw/openclaw.mjs config schema 2>&1 | grep -A5 -i \"routing\\|subagent\\|agent.*route\\|route.*agent\" | head -30"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":103570,"output":321,"cacheRead":21638,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":125529,"cost":{"input":0.031070999999999998,"output":0.0003852,"cacheRead":0.00129828,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.032754479999999996}},"stopReason":"toolUse","times