{"type":"message","id":"dd816300","parentId":"93ca7dc1","timestamp":"2026-04-18T02:56:01.025Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user wants me to test the automated routing. I need to send a high-scoring task. Let me think about what kind of message would score >= 40.\n\nI can't send a message through the webchat directly - the user controls that. But I can spawn a subagent in this session that will run and its result will be announced back here.\n\nActually, the better approach is: I can exec a curl to send a message via the gateway API, simulating what the user would do. Or I can verify the hook is working by checking logs.\n\nBut the user wants me to \"发挥主观能动性\" - take initiative. So let me think about the most proactive test:\n\n\nThe hook intercepts messages and checks their score. If it's >= 40, it prepends [AUTO_ROUTE] and modifies bodyForAgent before passing to the agent. So I need to either send a message through the webchat interface or call the gateway API directly to test if the hook is actually working.\n\nThe cleanest approach is using exec to curl the gateway with a high-scoring task and see if the response comes back with the [AUTO_ROUTE] prefix. The user's message will naturally be a multi-step task that scores high, and the hook will add the prefix before the agent sees it. I could also look at the gateway logs to verify the hook is running, or spawn a subagent to test the flow directly. Let me start with checking if I can send a test message to the gateway.\n\nActually, the most concrete next step is to send a message that will definitely score high—something like a complex multi-step coding request—and see if it gets the [AUTO_ROUTE] prefix added by the hook.\n\nBut I can't directly send a message to the webchat session from here. I could use exec to curl the gateway, but I don't have the right credentials. The better approach is to spawn a subagent that will generate a high-scoring task and send it through the webchat. Though thinking about it more carefully, spawning a subagent just sends its result back to me, not through the webchat to the user—so that's not actually testing the hook.\n\nI should just wait for the user to send a message. The hook is already running, they'll naturally send a task message, and the hook will intercept and process it. If the score is high enough, it will be routed accordingly.\n\nBut the user specifically asked me to take initiative, so maybe they're expecting me to do something proactive rather than just waiting. Perhaps they want me to analyze a project or perform some task directly, then based on the score, the hook would route it automatically. But that still requires a user message to trigger the hook in the first place.\n\nActually, I could write a test script that directly calls the hook handler or sends messages through the gateway to verify it's working.","thinkingSignature":"2b83ac154467e351629a3ffd821fa93ce1214c734906fc86287b814a923a1d4c"},{"type":"text","text":"我来主动触发测试——用 curl 向 gateway 发一条消息，验证 hook 是否注入了 `[AUTO_ROUTE]`：\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_hh9h1rcgbx7u_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"\n# 向 gateway 发一条高评分任务消息，看 hook 是否注入了 [AUTO_ROUTE]\n# 先查 gateway 端口和认证\nss -tlnp | grep -E \"18789|3100|3102\"\n"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":0,"output":678,"cacheRead":53906,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":54584,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0.0008135999999999999,"cacheRead":0.00323436,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.00404796}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776480936967,"responseId":"063225a8c39b42209b74571991491b60"}}
