{"type":"message","id":"d951f7a7","parentId":"8b4ae076","timestamp":"2026-04-18T03:14:40.491Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me take a step back and think about the architecture:\n\n1. The `openclaw-listener` process (PID 596) is the gateway's listener component\n2. The `openclaw-gateway` process (PID 8772) is the actual gateway\n3. Internal hooks are registered via `registerInternalHook()` which is a gateway-internal mechanism\n\nThe `context-hook.js` in `~/.openclaw/hooks/` is loaded through the `hooks.internal.entries.context_hook` config. The gateway must have a built-in loader that requires these hook files.\n\nThe key insight from the runtime schema comment was: \"Migrate each entry to a managed or workspace hook directory with HOOK.md + handler.js, then enable it through hooks.internal.entries.<hookKey> as needed.\"\n \nSo the gateway uses `hooks.internal.entries.<hookKey>` with a corresponding `handler.js` in the hook directory - that's the standard pattern. The `context_hook` entry has no path configured, which suggests the gateway resolves it relative to a base hooks directory. I need to figure out where that base directory is and whether `auto-score-classify` was ever actually registered as a plugin entry or just added to the config incorrectly.","thinkingSignature":"b9f303663b32c7d566d46ee2d6f4766000ac4fefde3e3da23520608e4fd95678"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_1kusxvd853dl_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"find ~/.openclaw/extensions -name \"*.json\" -o -name \"package.json\" 2>/dev/null | xargs grep -l \"auto-score-classify\" 2>/dev/null\n# Check if there's a plugin auto-score-classify\nls ~/.openclaw/extensions/"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":45234,"output":334,"cacheRead":21865,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":67433,"cost":{"input":0.0135702,"output":0.0004008,"cacheRead":0.0013119,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.015282899999999999}},"stopR