{"type":"message","id":"9252378c","parentId":"530968b0","timestamp":"2026-04-18T03:16:05.972Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I see the full picture:\n\n1. `openclaw-listener` connects to the Gateway via WebSocket\n2. When it receives a message, it calls 3104/3103 for classification/scoring\n3. It sends the message to the Gateway via `gatewayClient.send({ type: 'reply', content: reply })`\n\nThe key issue: `gatewayClient.send()` sends `{ type: 'reply', content: reply }` - this is a REPLY message type, not the original message with context! The classification/scoring results are just logged, never sent to the gateway.\n\nSo the real fix is to modify the `gatewayClient.send()` to include classification/scoring data in the message context that the gateway receives. \n\nI could either modify the GatewayClient to embed the scoring results in the WebSocket message it sends to the gateway, or find where the gateway's `message:preprocessed` hook is actually registered and understand how it receives context from the listener. Looking back at the code though, `gatewayClient.send()` with type 'reply' goes directly to the channel as a bot reply, not as an internal context update. The actual message flow from user to gateway must be happening through a different mechanism—likely the Feishu channel binding pushing messages in.\n\nIf the listener's `messageHandler.handle()` only does classification and scoring but then just sends a reply back through the channel, then the listener isn't actually forwarding the user's message to the gateway at all. I need to trace where the message is being routed to understand the full flow.","thinkingSignature":"45662f803eb181f49ae671a2b1e61d9b622b0173c47bf02774b24dc010c200d0"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_932utp8ea2im_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cat /home/ai/openclaw-listener/dist/main.js 2>/dev/null"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usa