{"type":"message","id":"bfb83427","parentId":"c54152b9","timestamp":"2026-04-18T04:30:45.251Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The context.json file exists but has 0 messages. So `tokens=0` is correct for this file. The gateway must be managing context in memory, not persisting it to context.json.\n\nThis means context-monitor reading from context.json will always show tokens=0 unless the gateway specifically writes to this file. The question is: does the gateway write to this file? Or is context.json just a placeholder that the gateway never writes to?\n\nIf context.json is always empty, then context-monitor will never trigger compression (since tokens=0 < 120000). This is a fundamental problem with the \"read from context.json\" approach.\n\nLet me check if there are other session context files with data:","thinkingSignature":"957eeb97ea5f3fc73c76a4728b30c7c73d41e94442d9186b672982ed48d9b579"},{"type":"text","text":"context.json 消息数组为空——gateway 内存里管 context，不写盘。检查其他 session：\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_yded3lwfxbts_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"for f in $(find ~/.openclaw/sessions -name \"context.json\" 2>/dev/null); do\n  msgs=$(python3 -c \"import json; d=json.load(open('$f')); print(len(d.get('messages',[])))\" 2>/dev/null)\n  echo \"$msgs $f\"\ndone | sort -rn | head -5"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":46064,"output":266,"cacheRead":21865,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":68195,"cost":{"input":0.0138192,"output":0.0003192,"cacheRead":0.0013119,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.0154503}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776486637214,"responseId":"06323bedc9f11a2f80357802a6ad6af7"}}
{"type":"message","id":"b62265fd","parentId":"bfb83427","timestamp":"2026-04-18T04:30:45.699Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_yded3lwfxbts_1","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"0 /home/ai/.openclaw/sessions/agent:main:main/context.json\n0 /home/ai/.openclaw/sessions/agent:main:cron:8f74a423-555b-468d-aac3-f8822b65bbcb/context.json\n0 /home/ai/.openclaw/sessions/agent:fast_agent:main/context.json\n0 /home/ai/.openclaw/sessions/agent:fast_agent:feishu:group:oc_1b955e738aa196d7f2afe9e1c1d35575/context.json\n0 /home/ai/.openclaw/sessions/agent:coder:main/context.json"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":221,"aggregated":"0 /home/ai/.openclaw/sessions/agent:main:main/context.json\n0 /home/ai/.openclaw/sessions/agent:main:cron:8f74a423-555b-468d-aac3-f8822b65bbcb/context.json\n0 /home/ai/.openclaw/sessions/agent:fast_agent:main/context.json\n0 /home/ai/.openclaw/sessions/agent:fast_agent:feishu:group:oc_1b955e738aa196d7f2afe9e1c1d35575/context.json\n0 /home/ai/.openclaw/sessions/agent:coder:main/context.json","cwd":"/home/ai/.openclaw/workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1776486645624}}
{"type":"message","id":"74f229ab","parentId":"b62265fd","timestamp":"2026-04-18T04:31:25.007Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"All context.json files have 0 messages. So the gateway doesn't write conversation history to context.json. The context is managed entirely in memory within the gateway process.\n\nThis means the context-monitor approach of reading context.json from the filesystem is fundamentally flawed for this gateway version. The context.json is not the right data source.\n\nI need to rethink this. Looking at the document \"完整功能框架.md\" for Context Engine:\n- \"Context Engine 上下文引擎\" — this is section 32\n- The context is managed by the gateway and passed to hooks via the event object\n\nBut wait, the ARCHITECTURE.md I generated earlier says:\n> **监控文件路径：**\n> ```\n> ${OPENCLAW_SESSION_CONTEXT_PATH}\n\n\n> 或 ${OPENCLAW_STATE_DIR}/sessions/agent:main:main/context.json\n> ```\n\nSo the original design intent was to read from context.json. But in reality, the gateway doesn't write to this file. The context is in memory.\n\nThis is a much bigger issue: either the context.json mechanism was designed but not implemented in the current gateway version, or it was removed in a newer version. Looking at the version stamp \"v2026.4.14\" versus the current \"lastTouchedVersion\": \"2026.4.15\", there might have been a change in how context is managed between these versions.\n\nGiven this incompatibility, context-monitor can't work as designed unless I can access the gateway's in-memory context somehow. The hook receives the event with `event.context`, but that's just the hook environment context, not the full conversation history. So the real question is whether the gateway exposes an API to retrieve the current session context, or if I need to find another way to access the in-memory context directly. the filesystem at all. Let me check the feishu cron session which is likely the most active. The fact that all context.json files show 0 messages is a clear sign that the gateway maintains context in memory only, and this file might be used for something else entirely or just left empty.\n\nI'm realizing the context-monitor approach of reading from context.json doesn't actually work in this setup. Rather than getting stuck on this, I should acknowledge this limitation to the user, document what I found, and move on to deploying the other components like the v8 Router or 3101 Context API that might actually be implementable.\n\nThough wait—the `tokens=0` results I'm seeing could mean the old handler was successfully reading context.json, just finding it empty, which would at least confirm the file reading mechanism works even if there's no data to read.\n\nLooking at the handler logic, if the file doesn't exist or has a parse error, it would silently return without logging anything. But we are seeing logs, so the file is being read successfully—it's just always empty. The new handler has the same read logic, so it should produce identical results. The real difference must be in how the event matching works or what the old handler was actually doing versus my new implementation.\n\nThe \"tokens=0\" log appears consistently every few minutes, which suggests either a recurring timer, repeated preprocessed events, or the old handler running on a different hook trigger entirely. Since we never see context-monitor logs after the restart at 12:27, the new handler clearly isn't firing the same way. At this point, the most honest approach is to acknowledge the reality: context-monitor can't function as designed because the gateway doesn't persist session context to disk, so the file will always be empty and the monitor will never detect actual token growth. I should report this finding and suggest the user either implement an alternative monitoring approach or accept this as a known limitation. Let me give the user a clear status report:\n\n1. context-monitor CANNOT work as designed because context.json is always empty (gateway manages context in memory, not in this file)\n2. The old \"tokens=0\" logs are from the PREVIOUS handler running, but reading an empty file\n3. The new handler was successfully deployed (7 handlers loaded vs 6 before) but has the same fundamental limitation\n4. Fixing this requires a different approach - either finding the gateway's internal context or not using context.json\n\nActually, let me reconsider. Maybe I should look at this from a different angle. What if instead of reading from context.json, I can get the token count from the hook event itself? Let me look at what data the gateway actually provides to hooks.\n\nThe hook event has access to sessionKey and bodyForAgent, which is the preprocessed message. But what about conversation history? That's where I need to think about what the gateway actually exposes versus what I'm trying to force into a file-based approach. The gateway might already be providing context data through the event itself, but I'm focused on reading from context.json when I should be checking what the hook event actually contains.\n\nLooking at the architecture docs, there should be an internal API at 3101 that hooks can call to get session context. That could be the real solution here - find out what 3101 actually does and whether it can give me the conversation state I need. But the problem is 3101 isn't running either, so even if that's the right path, I can't use it right now.\n\nI think the honest answer is that I've confirmed context-monitor is loaded as one of the 7 handlers, but it's stuck reading empty files because the gateway doesn't persist context to disk. This is a fundamental limitation that can't be fixed without either running the missing 3101 service or finding another way to access the gateway's internal context. I should report this clearly to the user and move on to the next fix.","thinkingSignature":"83faf1ef9c4bffc8efd24c57419e114c3a63101672f81248f2cdddc642a099d6"},{"type":"text","text":"### 确认的事实\n\n**context-monitor 已部署**（7 handlers loaded ✅），但有根本性问题：\n\n所有 `context.json` 文件消息数组为空——gateway **内存里管 context，不写盘**。所以无论新旧 handler，读到永远是 `tokens=0`，永远触发不了压缩。\n\n这不是我写坏了，是设计层面的不兼容——规格文档描述的 `context.json` 机制和当前 gateway 实际行为不符。\n\n---\n\n**当前状态确认**：\n\n| 操作 | 结果 |\n|------|------|\n| HOOK.md 修复 `---` 分隔符 | ✅ 完成 |\n| handler.js 改写 ESM | ✅ 完成 |\n| openclaw.json 加 context 配置 | ✅ 完成 |\n| context-monitor hook 加载 | ✅ 7 handlers（之前 6） |\n| 实际监控功能 | ❌ context.json 永远为空，无法工作 |\n\n---\n\n**我停下来等你说**：这个缺口需要想别的方案。你想继续修其他系统（3102 Router / 3101 Context API），还是先跳过 context-monitor？"}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":46486,"output":1373,"cacheRead":21865,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":69724,"cost":{"input":0.0139458,"output":0.0016476,"cacheRead":0.0013119,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.0169053}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1776486645701,"responseId":"06323bf4da30fcedd7ecea2dfd871cd3"}}
